Project 3: NFA Implementation
Author: Abdulalim Ciftci

Class: CS361 Section 001

Semester: Fall 2025

***OVERWIEW
-------------
This program implements a Nondeterministic Finite Automaton (NFA). 
It provides the ability to construct an automaton by adding states, defining an alphabet, setting a start state,
and adding final states.
The implementation fully supports transitions on symbols as well as epsilon ('e') transitions. 
The primary function of the program is to process a given input string and 
determine whether the NFA accepts or rejects that string.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
***REFLECTION
--------------
My experience with this project was challenging but definitely helpful for understanding automata. 
Getting the basic classes like NFAState and the simple methods in NFA (like addState, setStart) to work went pretty well. 
The main struggle was correctly implementing the eClosure method. 
It took several attempts to get the Stack-based (DFS) logic right, ensuring that it found all possible states 
reachable by epsilon moves, not just the first level. 
Since the accepts method depends entirely on eClosure, any bug there made accepts impossible to debug.

Even after finishing, the logic for the maxCopies method still feels a bit strange, 
especially since the "buggy" version (updating the max inside the inner loop) was the one that passed the tests. 
This makes me think I might still be missing a subtle point about how it's supposed to be calculated versus the accepts logic. 
To debug my code, my main technique was adding System.out.println statements inside the accepts loop to print the 
currentStates set after processing each character. 
This was the only way I could "see" where the machine was going and why it was failing.

If I could go back in time, I would tell myself to write a separate, small test for eClosure before trying to write accepts. 
All my problems came from that method. I also changed my design halfway through. 
I originally used a HashSet to store all states, but finding a state by name was slow (I had to loop). 
I changed this to a HashMap<String, NFAState> which made the getState method instant and cleaned up the 
addTransition logic significantly. I would definitely use a Map from the beginning next time.
